16.Your organization runs applications across AWS, Azure, and GCP and wants to standardize their infrastructure deployment process. Which Terraform capability best addresses this requirement?
Multi-cloud deployment is a core Terraform use case. Terraform lets you use the same workflow (Write, Plan, Apply) to manage multiple providers and handle cross-cloud dependencies, simplifying management and orchestration for large-scale, multi-cloud infrastructures.

17.Select all the true statements about using the moved block. (select three
The moved block is designed for refactoring resource addresses within a single Terraform state file. 
It can handle renaming individual resources, moving resources into or out of modules, and even renaming entire modules. 
Before creating a moved block, you must write the new resource block with the destination address. Once you've applied the changes, 
the moved block becomes unnecessary temporary scaffolding and should be deleted. The critical limitation is that moved blocks only work within the same state file — 
if you need to transfer resources between different state files, you must use removed blocks in the source and import blocks in the destination configuration.

18.A colleague has two provider "aws" blocks (one for us-east-1, one for eu-west-1) and is getting an error. The DynamoDB resource references provider = aws.europe. 
Which change will fix the configuration?
Terraform allows you to define multiple configurations of the same provider by using the "alias" meta-argument on additional provider blocks. 
The first provider block without an alias becomes the default configuration, and any additional configurations must include alias so Terraform can distinguish between them.
Resources then reference a non-default provider using the provider meta-argument with the syntax provider = <PROVIDER>.<ALIAS>. Without the alias, Terraform cannot resolve 
the aws.europe reference and will throw an error during planning.





















